  "prompt": "What are some good science documentaries, other than Stephen Hawking's Grand Design?",
  "response": "Certainly! Here are some excellent science documentaries that you might enjoy:\n\n1. **Cosmos: A Spacetime Odyssey** - Hosted by Neil deGrasse Tyson, this series explores the wonders of the universe, the laws of nature, and the scientific discoveries that have shaped our understanding of the cosmos.\n\n2. **Planet Earth** - This documentary series by the BBC, narrated by David Attenborough, offers breathtaking visuals and insights into the natural world, covering various ecosystems and wildlife across the planet.\n\n3. **The Universe** - This History Channel series delves into the mysteries of the cosmos, covering topics such as black holes, the big bang, and the possibility of extraterrestrial life.\n\n4. **Particle Fever** - This documentary follows physicists as they attempt to unravel the mysteries of the universe through the Large Hadron Collider and the discovery of the Higgs boson.\n\n5. **Nova** - A long-running PBS series that covers a wide range of scientific topics, from space exploration and physics to biology and technology.\n\n6. **The Farthest: Voyager in Space** - This documentary chronicles the Voyager spacecraft missions, highlighting their journey through the solar system and beyond.\n\n7. **Black Hole Apocalypse** - Part of the Nova series, this documentary explores the fascinating and terrifying nature of black holes.\n\n8. **Chasing Ice** - This film documents the efforts of photographer James Balog to capture evidence of climate change through stunning time-lapse photography of melting glaciers.\n\n9. **The Secret Life of Chaos** - This BBC documentary examines the principles of chaos theory and how it applies to the natural world.\n\n10. **An Inconvenient Truth** - Al Gore's documentary on climate change, presenting the scientific evidence and the potential impacts on the planet.\n\nThese documentaries offer a diverse range of topics and compelling insights into the wonders and complexities of science.",
